    <!-- SIMULATIONS -->
    <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">
      Simulations
    </h2>

    <div class="mt-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed space-y-4">
      <p>
        One of my main tasks was to develop precise physics simulations of particle behaviour in PUMA.
        These simulations were used to verify assumptions and experimental results, as well as to better
        understand interactions in PUMA’s drift region.
      </p>

      <p>
        All simulations were developed on Linux (Ubuntu) and run inside a Singularity container via SSH
        on TRIUMF’s local computing resources. I used COMSOL Multiphysics (electrostatics module) to
        generate a field map and mesh for integration with Garfield++.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Fig 7–8 -->
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mt-8">
      <figure><div class="w-full aspect-square bg-gray-200 rounded-md shadow-lg"></div><figcaption class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-500 text-center">Fig. 7: PUMA potential model</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><div class="w-full aspect-square bg-gray-200 rounded-md shadow-lg"></div><figcaption class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-500 text-center">Fig. 8: PUMA electric field model</figcaption></figure>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed space-y-4">
      <p>
        Garfield++ is a C++ library developed by CERN for detailed simulation of particle detectors.
        I used the DriftLineRKF and TrackHeed classes to simulate electron drift in gaseous argon and
        later in liquid xenon.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Fig 9 -->
    <figure class="mt-8">
      <div class="w-full aspect-[4/3] bg-gray-200 rounded-md shadow-lg"></div>
